snippet.textDisplay:
You should have checked out the face-shield Joel was testing before starting to massproduce the Prusa one. If the shortage of faceshields really is the problem wouldn't 3-6 times as many be better?

Sure I'm all for the central coordination but i'm saddened by this huge waste of potential. The one Joel was testing is the approved standard one in Sweden, and is designed for function first and efficiency of production second. Unlike the prusa one that is designed as a prusa advertisement first, some mediocre function and no efficiency of production. With a fast printer they are done in 20-30 min, every printer can do them in less than an hour. Compared to the 3hrs for the prusa one. oh and they dont need the elastic band either, so one less thing to source and disinfect.

snippet.textDisplay:
In these days and times, it's nice to remember President Kenedys words, slightly rewritten: "Ask not: What van my health care system do for me, ask: What can I do to keep health care staying alive!" Here in Denmark, our communities of Maker Space and Fab-Lab started producing face shields two weeks ago, and they asked all public offices to donate all their lamination pockets and overhead foils, and every one with a 3D printer is now working on the project. Every niche producer of beer and spirits have changed their objective to produce alcohol for sanitizing.
Half the World is stepping up to the plate, doing what they can to help their fellow humans, while the other half is whining about having to stay home for a few weeks, so I guess the Apokalypse has been postponed for a while now, and there's still hope for human kind :)
An other thing that has sprung out of this mayhem, is people who are volunteering to help those who are affected by the virus, by doing grocery shopping and other chores, so those in quarantine can stay at home, all organized by our local Red Cross and local FB groups.
It's heart warming to see how help is always given to those who needs it, even in the face of doom :)

For flattening the curve please anyone who can give me advice, I would love to hear it. My first instinct was hospitals and medical workers, of course, but I also can't help but think of stopping the problem at the source?

snippet.textDisplay: I think your intentions are good, but this is nothing like what we use in the front line medical field.  Face masks are disposable equipment and are meant to fit more universally.  Rigid 3D printed and injection molded headbands do not fit universally and are much too costly to make.  I have a 3D printer and have used injection molding in medical prototypes.  You're wasting too much time.  The ones we have used for years have a sponge headband and velcro straps.  They are cost effective and are a throw away item.  Face shields are not meant to be sterile equipment, so better check with the local hospital as to your cleaning solutions so that it can be used in their hospital without causing contact allergies.  When one has a 3D printer one's solution is to 3D print the solution.  Much like having a hammer and everything looks like a nail.  3D printing is much too time consuming and costly for this solution.  And you would have to make too many different sizes to fit to each head shape.  A gap in the fit is not good.  Foam is much more economical and fits any size and contour head, man or woman.  It is much more comfortable, and cheap enough to just toss like disposable gloves.   Why change what has been working well for decades. You are overthinking the solution.  Your time may be better spent getting the public to wear surgical face masks when outside of the house.  Huntsville has shot up to 165 cases today, so more needs to be done to inform the public so that the front line medical staff doesn't need to be seeing too many of them.
